                      <span>3</span>
                      /
                      <span>5</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2001-10-08</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I agree, the book is excellent. COM+ is one of those complicated subjects that, when mastered (is that possible?) can make your like SOOO much easier.<BR> Beware, though: some of the author's comments are opinions, not facts. Take this one: "From a scalability point of view, it's better to conduct multiple operations inside stored procedures." Ouch. I HOPE he meant PERFORMANCE, not SCALABILITY, because that statement not only breaks one of the main benefits of stored procedures (code reuse; if you have your SP doing multiple things it's much less likely that you'll be able to use it somewhere else); it also breaks one of the main benefits of scalability (the ability to easily scale out pools of objects that are agnostic about their data source).<BR> But hey, it's a Microsoft Press book, so in fairness, he probably doesn't want us thinking about how to scale mySQL {:-}, as I seem to be doing these days...</span>
                  
              
